Cell.Data: Select the specimens to be extracted on the "coll" sheet (read-only) and paste them into the "extr" sheet as a full row. Extractions should be done in multiples of 8.

Copy the calculation fields on the right of the "extr" sheet (columns AR to AY) onto the new extractions. Add the specimen number in column AP. Format for the specimen number is [catalog number].x, e.g. "m102-04.1". Make sure to check previous extractions to make sure there are no duplicate specimen numbers (you can do this by sorting by the specimen number column).

Add a new sheet to this workbook, paste in the info for the new extractions, and print it out (if any changes are made later, make sure to update the spreadsheet). Name the sheet with the date of the extraction (in the format 091215 for Dec. 15, 2009).
For each specimen, allow alcohol to fully evaporate on a kimwipe (use a separate section for each individual).
Examine the specimen for debris, mites, and dryness under the microscope.
Place in a labelled microcentrifuge tube for extraction.
After the lysis step, rinse each specimen and place in 95% EtOH in a glass screw-cap vial and a label with the extraction number AND the specimen number.
Proceed with the extraction by the normal protocol.
Store the data sheet in a 3-ring binder and specimens in a box in the refrigerator or freezer.
